<p><b>  Report of the Special Rapporteur on the independence of 
judges and lawyers, Gabriela Knaul</b>&#8727;<b> </b>&#8727;&#8727;<b> 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Annex 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Subregional consultation on the independence of the judiciary in 
Central America 
</b></p>
<p> <i>Summary</i> 
 On 28 and 29 November 2012, the Special Rapporteur on the independence of 
judges and lawyers held a consultation in Panama City on the independence of the judiciary 
in Central America. The present report provides information on the judicial structure of 
each country and on challenges to the independence of the judiciary, such as the procedures 
for the selection, appointment or election of magistrates and judges; it also contains 
conclusions and recommendations. 
</p>
<p> On the first day, the consultation was attended by experts in the judicial service, 
academics and representatives of civil society, the Inter-American Commission on Human 
Rights and the OHCHR Regional Office for the seven countries in the region. On the 
second day, a meeting was held with Government representatives of countries of the region, 
who presented their views on current procedures, good practices, and obstacles and 
challenges to the independence of the judiciary at regional level. 
</p>
<p>  
</p>
<p> &#8727; The summary of this report is being circulated in all official languages. The report itself is contained 
in the annex to the summary and is being circulated in Spanish and English only. 
</p>
<p> &#8727;&#8727; Late submission. 
</p>
<p> United Nations A/HRC/23/43/Add.4
</p>
